1
0:00:12.76,000 --> 0:00:13,000
When I was first learning to meditate,

2
0:00:14.64,000 --> 0:00:17,000
the instruction was to simply pay attention to my breath,

3
0:00:17.72,000 --> 0:00:19,000
and when my mind wandered, to bring it back.

4
0:00:20.64,000 --> 0:00:21,000
Sounded simple enough.

5
0:00:22.68,000 --> 0:00:25,000
Yet I'd sit on these silent retreats,

6
0:00:25.92,000 --> 0:00:28,000
sweating through T-shirts in the middle of winter.

7
0:00:29.28,000 --> 0:00:32,000
I'd take naps every chance I got because it was really hard work.

8
0:00:32.64,000 --> 0:00:34,000
Actually, it was exhausting.

9
0:00:35.4,000 --> 0:00:36,000
The instruction was simple enough

10
0:00:37.16,000 --> 0:00:39,000
but I was missing something really important.

11
0:00:40.32,000 --> 0:00:42,000
So why is it so hard to pay attention?

12
0:00:43.08,000 --> 0:00:44,000
Well, studies show

13
0:00:44.56,000 --> 0:00:47,000
that even when we're really trying to pay attention to something --

14
0:00:47.76,000 --> 0:00:48,000
like maybe this talk --

15
0:00:49.36,000 --> 0:00:5,000
at some point,

16
0:00:50.6,000 --> 0:00:52,000
about half of us will drift off into a daydream,

17
0:00:52.96,000 --> 0:00:54,000
or have this urge to check our Twitter feed.

18
0:00:56.36,000 --> 0:00:57,000
So what's going on here?

19
0:00:59,000 --> 0:01:02,000
It turns out that we're fighting one of the most evolutionarily-conserved

20
0:01:02.48,000 --> 0:01:04,000
learning processes currently known in science,

21
0:01:05.36,000 --> 0:01:06,000
one that's conserved

22
0:01:06.6,000 --> 0:01:08,000
back to the most basic nervous systems known to man.

23
0:01:09.84,000 --> 0:01:1,000
This reward-based learning process

24
0:01:11.52,000 --> 0:01:13,000
is called positive and negative reinforcement,

25
0:01:13.72,000 --> 0:01:14,000
and basically goes like this.

26
0:01:16.2,000 --> 0:01:17,000
We see some food that looks good,

27
0:01:17.92,000 --> 0:01:19,000
our brain says, "Calories! ... Survival!"

28
0:01:20.64,000 --> 0:01:21,000
We eat the food, we taste it --

29
0:01:22.16,000 --> 0:01:23,000
it tastes good.

30
0:01:23.4,000 --> 0:01:24,000
And especially with sugar,

31
0:01:24.96,000 --> 0:01:26,000
our bodies send a signal to our brain that says,

32
0:01:27.24,000 --> 0:01:29,000
"Remember what you're eating and where you found it."

33
0:01:31.28,000 --> 0:01:33,000
We lay down this context-dependent memory

34
0:01:34.04,000 --> 0:01:36,000
and learn to repeat the process next time.

35
0:01:36.52,000 --> 0:01:37,000
See food,

36
0:01:37.76,000 --> 0:01:38,000
eat food, feel good,

37
0:01:39.48,000 --> 0:01:4,000
repeat.

38
0:01:40.96,000 --> 0:01:42,000
Trigger, behavior, reward.

39
0:01:43.6,000 --> 0:01:44,000
Simple, right?

40
0:01:45.92,000 --> 0:01:47,000
Well, after a while, our creative brains say,

41
0:01:48.08,000 --> 0:01:49,000
"You know what?

42
0:01:49.32,000 --> 0:01:52,000
You can use this for more than just remembering where food is.

43
0:01:52.96,000 --> 0:01:54,000
You know, next time you feel bad,

44
0:01:55.16,000 --> 0:01:58,000
why don't you try eating something good so you'll feel better?"

45
0:01:59.72,000 --> 0:02:01,000
We thank our brains for the great idea,

46
0:02:01.76,000 --> 0:02:02,000
try this and quickly learn

47
0:02:03.36,000 --> 0:02:06,000
that if we eat chocolate or ice cream when we're mad or sad,

48
0:02:06.68,000 --> 0:02:07,000
we feel better.

49
0:02:08.64,000 --> 0:02:09,000
Same process,

50
0:02:10.04,000 --> 0:02:11,000
just a different trigger.

51
0:02:11.8,000 --> 0:02:14,000
Instead of this hunger signal coming from our stomach,

52
0:02:14.92,000 --> 0:02:15,000
this emotional signal -- feeling sad --

53
0:02:16.92,000 --> 0:02:17,000
triggers that urge to eat.

54
0:02:19.04,000 --> 0:02:2,000
Maybe in our teenage years,

55
0:02:21.199,000 --> 0:02:22,000
we were a nerd at school,

56
0:02:23.6,000 --> 0:02:25,000
and we see those rebel kids outside smoking and we think,

57
0:02:26.32,000 --> 0:02:27,000
"Hey, I want to be cool."

58
0:02:27.6,000 --> 0:02:28,000
So we start smoking.

59
0:02:29.8,000 --> 0:02:32,000
The Marlboro Man wasn't a dork, and that was no accident.

60
0:02:33.56,000 --> 0:02:34,000
See cool,

61
0:02:34.8,000 --> 0:02:35,000
smoke to be cool,

62
0:02:36.12,000 --> 0:02:37,000
feel good. Repeat.

63
0:02:37.96,000 --> 0:02:39,000
Trigger, behavior, reward.

64
0:02:40.64,000 --> 0:02:41,000
And each time we do this,

65
0:02:41.92,000 --> 0:02:43,000
we learn to repeat the process

66
0:02:43.96,000 --> 0:02:44,000
and it becomes a habit.

67
0:02:45.92,000 --> 0:02:46,000
So later,

68
0:02:47.24,000 --> 0:02:5,000
feeling stressed out triggers that urge to smoke a cigarette

69
0:02:50.88,000 --> 0:02:51,000
or to eat something sweet.

70
0:02:53.2,000 --> 0:02:55,000
Now, with these same brain processes,

71
0:02:56.16,000 --> 0:02:57,000
we've gone from learning to survive

72
0:02:58.08,000 --> 0:03:,000
to literally killing ourselves with these habits.

73
0:03:00.96,000 --> 0:03:01,000
Obesity and smoking

74
0:03:02.24,000 --> 0:03:06,000
are among the leading preventable causes of morbidity and mortality in the world.

75
0:03:07.48,000 --> 0:03:08,000
So back to my breath.

76
0:03:09.72,000 --> 0:03:11,000
What if instead of fighting our brains,

77
0:03:12.12,000 --> 0:03:14,000
or trying to force ourselves to pay attention,

78
0:03:14.68,000 --> 0:03:18,000
we instead tapped into this natural, reward-based learning process ...

79
0:03:18.72,000 --> 0:03:19,000
but added a twist?

80
0:03:20.52,000 --> 0:03:22,000
What if instead we just got really curious

81
0:03:22.6,000 --> 0:03:24,000
about what was happening in our momentary experience?

82
0:03:25.12,000 --> 0:03:26,000
I'll give you an example.

83
0:03:26.68,000 --> 0:03:27,000
In my lab,

84
0:03:27.92,000 --> 0:03:3,000
we studied whether mindfulness training could help people quit smoking.

85
0:03:31.28,000 --> 0:03:34,000
Now, just like trying to force myself to pay attention to my breath,

86
0:03:34.96,000 --> 0:03:37,000
they could try to force themselves to quit smoking.

87
0:03:38.24,000 --> 0:03:4,000
And the majority of them had tried this before and failed --

88
0:03:41.2,000 --> 0:03:42,000
