0:03:52.84,000 --> 0:03:53,000
What? Yeah, we said, "Go ahead and smoke,

93
0:03:54.84,000 --> 0:03:57,000
just be really curious about what it's like when you do."

94
0:03:58.4,000 --> 0:03:59,000
And what did they notice?

95
0:04:00.12,000 --> 0:04:02,000
Well here's an example from one of our smokers.

96
0:04:02.84,000 --> 0:04:03,000
She said, "Mindful smoking:

97
0:04:04.6,000 --> 0:04:05,000
smells like stinky cheese

98
0:04:06.24,000 --> 0:04:07,000
and tastes like chemicals,

99
0:04:07.88,000 --> 0:04:08,000
YUCK!"

100
0:04:09.68,000 --> 0:04:12,000
Now, she knew, cognitively that smoking was bad for her,

101
0:04:13.08,000 --> 0:04:14,000
that's why she joined our program.

102
0:04:15.68,000 --> 0:04:19,000
What she discovered just by being curiously aware when she smoked

103
0:04:20.24,000 --> 0:04:23,000
was that smoking tastes like shit.

104
0:04:23.4,000 --> 0:04:24,000
(Laughter)

105
0:04:26.36,000 --> 0:04:3,000
Now, she moved from knowledge to wisdom.

106
0:04:30.399,000 --> 0:04:33,000
She moved from knowing in her head that smoking was bad for her

107
0:04:33.519,000 --> 0:04:35,000
to knowing it in her bones,

108
0:04:36,000 --> 0:04:38,000
and the spell of smoking was broken.

109
0:04:38.32,000 --> 0:04:41,000
She started to become disenchanted with her behavior.

110
0:04:42.96,000 --> 0:04:44,000
Now, the prefrontal cortex,

111
0:04:45.08,000 --> 0:04:48,000
that youngest part of our brain from an evolutionary perspective,

112
0:04:48.64,000 --> 0:04:52,000
it understands on an intellectual level that we shouldn't smoke.

113
0:04:52.72,000 --> 0:04:55,000
And it tries its hardest to help us change our behavior,

114
0:04:56.56,000 --> 0:04:57,000
to help us stop smoking,

115
0:04:57.92,000 --> 0:05:01,000
to help us stop eating that second, that third, that fourth cookie.

116
0:05:02.96,000 --> 0:05:03,000
We call this cognitive control.

117
0:05:04.48,000 --> 0:05:06,000
We're using cognition to control our behavior.

118
0:05:07.96,000 --> 0:05:08,000
Unfortunately,

119
0:05:09.2,000 --> 0:05:1,000
this is also the first part of our brain

120
0:05:11.16,000 --> 0:05:13,000
that goes offline when we get stressed out,

121
0:05:13.2,000 --> 0:05:14,000
which isn't that helpful.

122
0:05:14.48,000 --> 0:05:16,000
Now, we can all relate to this in our own experience.

123
0:05:16.981,000 --> 0:05:19,000
We're much more likely to do things like yell at our spouse or kids

124
0:05:20.16,000 --> 0:05:21,000
when we're stressed out or tired,

125
0:05:21.8,000 --> 0:05:23,000
even though we know it's not going to be helpful.

126
0:05:24.16,000 --> 0:05:25,000
We just can't help ourselves.

127
0:05:27.12,000 --> 0:05:29,000
When the prefrontal cortex goes offline,

128
0:05:29.32,000 --> 0:05:31,000
we fall back into our old habits,

129
0:05:31.56,000 --> 0:05:33,000
which is why this disenchantment is so important.

130
0:05:34.44,000 --> 0:05:35,000
Seeing what we get from our habits

131
0:05:36.12,000 --> 0:05:38,000
helps us understand them at a deeper level --

132
0:05:38.32,000 --> 0:05:39,000
to know it in our bones

133
0:05:39.6,000 --> 0:05:41,000
so we don't have to force ourselves to hold back

134
0:05:41.88,000 --> 0:05:42,000
or restrain ourselves from behavior.

135
0:05:43.64,000 --> 0:05:45,000
We're just less interested in doing it in the first place.

136
0:05:46.44,000 --> 0:05:48,000
And this is what mindfulness is all about:

137
0:05:49,000 --> 0:05:52,000
Seeing really clearly what we get when we get caught up in our behaviors,

138
0:05:53.56,000 --> 0:05:56,000
becoming disenchanted on a visceral level

139
0:05:57.16,000 --> 0:06:,000
and from this disenchanted stance, naturally letting go.

140
0:06:00.92,000 --> 0:06:03,000
This isn't to say that, poof, magically we quit smoking.

141
0:06:04.44,000 --> 0:06:06,000
But over time, as we learn to see more and more clearly

142
0:06:07.08,000 --> 0:06:08,000
the results of our actions,

143
0:06:08.44,000 --> 0:06:1,000
we let go of old habits and form new ones.

144
0:06:12.12,000 --> 0:06:13,000
The paradox here

145
0:06:13.48,000 --> 0:06:15,000
is that mindfulness is just about being really interested

146
0:06:16.32,000 --> 0:06:17,000
in getting close and personal

147
0:06:17.76,000 --> 0:06:19,000
with what's actually happening in our bodies and minds

148
0:06:20.36,000 --> 0:06:21,000
from moment to moment.

149
0:06:22,000 --> 0:06:24,000
This willingness to turn toward our experience

150
0:06:24.32,000 --> 0:06:27,000
rather than trying to make unpleasant cravings go away as quickly as possible.

151
0:06:28.76,000 --> 0:06:3,000
And this willingness to turn toward our experience

152
0:06:31.36,000 --> 0:06:32,000
is supported by curiosity,

153
0:06:33.24,000 --> 0:06:34,000
which is naturally rewarding.

154
0:06:35,000 --> 0:06:36,000
What does curiosity feel like?

155
0:06:36.76,000 --> 0:06:37,000
It feels good.

156
0:06:39.04,000 --> 0:06:41,000
And what happens when we get curious?

157
0:06:41.37,000 --> 0:06:44,000
We start to notice that cravings are simply made up of body sensations --

158
0:06:44.84,000 --> 0:06:46,000
oh, there's tightness, there's tension,

159
0:06:47.12,000 --> 0:06:48,000
there's restlessness --

160
0:06:48.8,000 --> 0:06:5,000
and that these body sensations come and go.

161
0:06:51.88,000 --> 0:06:53,000
These are bite-size pieces of experiences

162
0:06:54.88,000 --> 0:06:56,000
that we can manage from moment to moment

163
0:06:56.92,000 --> 0:07:,000
rather than getting clobbered by this huge, scary craving

164
0:07:01.08,000 --> 0:07:02,000
that we choke on.

165
0:07:02.48,000 --> 0:07:04,000
In other words, when we get curious,

166
0:07:05,000 --> 0:07:09,000
we step out of our old, fear-based, reactive habit patterns,

167
0:07:09.76,000 --> 0:07:11,000
and we step into being.

168
0:07:12,000 --> 0:07:14,000
We become this inner scientist

169
0:07:14.92,000 --> 0:07:17,000
where we're eagerly awaiting that next data point.

170
0:07:18.16,000 --> 0:07:22,000
Now, this might sound too simplistic to affect behavior.

171
0:07:22.72,000 --> 0:07:24,000
But in one study, we found that mindfulness training

172
0:07:25.2,000 --> 0:07:28,000
was twice as good as gold standard therapy at helping people quit smoking.

173
0:07:29.12,000 --> 0:07:3,000
So it actually works.

